data.content:
Great question. Looking at your `ReportGenerator`, you actually have **four** categories of untestable statics:

| Category | Calls found | Best abstraction |
|----------|------------|------------------|
| **File system** | `File.WriteAllText`, `Directory.Exists`, `Directory.CreateDirectory` | `System.IO.Abstractions` (NuGet) |
| **Time** | `DateTime.UtcNow` (Ă—2) | `TimeProvider` (built-in on .NET 10) |
| **Environment** | `GetEnvironmentVariable`, `MachineName` | Custom `IEnvironmentProvider` |
| **Console** | `Console.WriteLine` | Custom `IConsole` (or just use `ILogger`) |

Here's the recommended approach for each:

---

### 1. File System â†’ `System.IO.Abstractions`

Don't write a custom wrapper â€” use the battle-tested NuGet package:

```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

Register in DI:
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

Inject into your class:
```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    // Use fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(...) instead of File.WriteAllText(...)
    // Use fileSystem.Directory.Exists(...) instead of Directory.Exists(...)
}
```

Test with `MockFileSystem`:
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem();
mockFs.AddDirectory("/tmp/reports");
var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs, ...);
```

---

### 2. Time â†’ `TimeProvider` (built-in)

You're on .NET 10, so no NuGet needed. Register and inject:

```csharp
// DI registration
builder.Services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);

// In your class
public class ReportGenerator(IFileSystem fileSystem, TimeProvider timeProvider)
{
    var timestamp = timeProvider.GetUtcNow().ToString("yyyyMMdd_HHmmss");
}
```

Test with `FakeTimeProvider`:
```
dotnet add <TestProject> package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
```
```csharp
var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(
    new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 10, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var generator = new ReportGenerator(mockFs, fakeTime, ...);
```

---

### 3. Environment â†’ Custom minimal wrapper

Only wrap the two methods you actually use:

```csharp
public interface IEnvironmentProvider
{
    string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable);
    string MachineName { get; }
}

public sealed class EnvironmentProvider : IEnvironmentProvider
{
    public string? GetEnvironmentVariable(string variable)
        => Environment.GetEnvironmentVariable(variable);
    public string MachineName => Environment.MachineName;
}

// DI: builder.Services.AddSingleton<IEnvironmentProvider, EnvironmentProvider>();
```

---

### 4. Refactored `ReportGenerator`

Putting it all together:

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator(
    IFileSystem fileSystem,
    TimeProvider timeProvider,
    IEnvironmentProvider environment)
{
    public string GenerateReport(string reportName)
    {
        var now = timeProvider.GetUtcNow();
        var timestamp = now.ToString("yyyyMMdd_HHmmss");
        var outputDir = environment.GetEnvironmentVariable("REPORT_OUTPUT_DIR") ?? "/tmp/reports";

        if (!fileSystem.Directory.Exists(outputDir))
        {
            fileSystem.Directory.CreateDirectory(outputDir);
        }

        var reportPath = fileSystem.Path.Combine(outputDir, $"{reportName}_{timestamp}.txt");
        var content = $"Report: {reportName}\nGenerated: {now:O}\nMachine: {environment.MachineName}";

        fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(reportPath, content);

        return reportPath;
    }
}
```

Every dependency is now injectable and mockable. The `Console.WriteLine` was dropped since it's a side-effect better handled by `ILogger<T>` if you need it.

